## F. Technical Architecture

### F1. Tech Stack

| Layer | Choice |
|---|---|
| **Framework** | Astro JS 5.x — SSG mode, islands architecture |
| **Styling** | Tailwind CSS 4.x + CSS variables using `@theme` |
| **Language** | TypeScript — strict mode, for data models and utilities |
| **Icons** | Lucide Icons — via `lucide` package |
| **Images** | `@astrojs/image` — automatic WebP conversion, lazy loading |
| **Forms** | Netlify Forms (static) or Formspree — zero backend needed |
| **Maps** | Google Maps iframe embed (no API key needed for embed) |
| **Analytics** | Google Analytics 4 + Microsoft Clarity (via Partytown) |
| **SEO** | Custom `SEO.astro` component + JSON-LD schema |
| **Deployment** | Netlify or Vercel (auto-deploy on GitHub push) |
| **Version Control** | GitHub — main branch deploys to production |
| **Node.js** | 20.x LTS |

### F2. Astro JS Architecture Decisions

#### Why Astro?

- Zero JavaScript by default — pure HTML/CSS output = fastest possible load times.
- Islands architecture — interactive components (gallery filter, FAQ accordion, carousel) load JS only when needed.
- Content Collections — built-in typed content management from Markdown/JSON files.
- SEO-perfect — server-rendered HTML, no hydration delay for search crawlers.
- File-based routing — `/src/pages/about.astro` = `/about` URL automatically.
- Easy migration path — swap SSG to SSR by adding an adapter (Netlify/Vercel) when Phase 2 is ready.

#### Content Strategy: Static Content Layer

In Phase 1, all content lives in structured data files:

| File | Content |
|---|---|
| `/src/data/school.json` | School metadata, contact info, social links |
| `/src/data/events.json` | Events |
| `/src/data/gallery.json` | Gallery |
| `/src/data/testimonials.json` | Testimonials |
| `/src/data/faqs.json` | FAQs |
| `/src/data/programs.json` | Classes/Programmes |
| `/src/data/team.json` | Team members |
| `/src/data/facilities.json` | Facilities |
| `/src/data/admissions.json` | Admission steps |

> In Phase 2, these JSON files are replaced by API calls to the CMS. The Astro components remain identical — only the data source changes.

